posts.cooked:
Our RoboRIO (1.0) keeps running out of memory running our robot program.

The crash is not an out of memory error but rather a full JVM crash , which makes me feel like the JVM is allocating the memory it should use.

I used VisualVM to profile the memory usage but I couldn’t find anything that would obviously eat up memory in our robot program, and the program was only using about 100 mb maximum of the heap.

However, this is was in the simulator, not on the robot. I can’t get a profiler to start on the RoboRIO because it eats up even more memory and crashes before I can connect. I also can’t get a heap dump because I don’t seem to have commands like jmap or jcmd , and because the JVM is crashing, it won’t produce a heap dump using -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError .

I’ve tried a couple of fixes from WPILIb , and while the robot is seemingly stable doing nothing, free -m only reports about 2mb of free memory, and I never got the chance to enable the robot yesterday to see if any commands would eat up the rest of that. Just seems like a bandaid solution to me.

Not sure where to go from here, so I’m calling on some help before our next competition.

Robot code: Link | Working Branch | [Attempted Fixes] ( perf: various memory conservation attempts · frc5183/octavian@e7f171f · GitHub )

Thanks

posts.name: jdao
posts.cooked:
Have you tried adding a swap file on a USB from that page? Java Garbage Collection — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation

If you’re getting immediate crashes and don’t have a roboRIO 2, then this is probably your only option. Make sure your USB is good (test that the RIO can see it and test that it can do constant reads/writes, some cheap Amazon USBs have cheap controllers that will batch read/write for a minute, then hang for another minute).

Given that you are using AdvantageKit as well, I’m not sure that you have any easy code fixes due to how it works. See some of the discussion on this from previous yearsfor reference.

posts.cooked:
Yeah… I figured it was just kind of end of the road for tuning and random modifications.

I haven’t added a swap file on a USB drive yet, I didn’t have one yesterday to test with, any recommendations? I’d imagine reliability and speed are important with swap.

Any recommendations for mounting methods either? Definitely don’t want it to fall out.

Also, do you think it’d be fine to run swap and advantagekit logging on the same usb drive? Or would you do another method to give as much bandwidth to that swap file?

Also, would you recommend undoing the changes made (manual GC calls, JVM args, sysctl etc.) once we have a USB drive with swap? Whether it’s to improve stability or just to keep everything else stock.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Have you tried disabling the system webserver?  That’s one of the easiest ways to free up a bunch of memory.
Yup, didn’t make a dent, in top I think it was only using about 2% of the memory.

posts.name: jdao
posts.cooked:
Any USB should be fine, as long as there are no glaring issues. Large USBs (>64 GB) may run into issues due to needing a different format other than FAT, which the roboRIO won’t recognize. I personally prefer USB’s with a small physical footprint like these . They usually fit snugly into the USB port without any particular mounting considerations.

If I remember correctly, I believe the issue is mostly related to the JVM requesting a lot of memory for initialization and the actual usage is low, so it doesn’t really use the swap file during runtime. Using the same USB for AdvantageKit logging and the swap file shouldn’t cause any issues.

link_counts.title: Amazon.com: SanDisk 32GB Ultra Fit USB 3.1 Flash Drive - SDCZ430-032G-G46 : Electronics

posts.cooked:
Yeah, we just grabbed a high quality, slim profile SanDisk and made a mounting bracket to make sure it won’t slip out easily.

I also think the issue is from the JVM overallocating or allocating a lot at startup, because in the profiler we’re barely touching 160mb. It would also explain why setting the sysctl vm.overcommit_memory to 1 on the RIO worked, since it’s not actually really using any of that memory.

Nonetheless, I’m personally gonna stick to a swap file on a USB drive and set vm.overcommit_memory back to 2, just in case we ever somehow need that memory.
